Description from the publisher:

Things are definitely getting weird in Undimensioned and Unseen, the fourth Mythos Pack in The Dunwich Legacy cycle for Arkham Horror: The Card Game&hellip;

By the time your pursuit of two missing professors leads you to the scenario from Undimensioned and Unseen, you'll have traveled far from the familiar comforts of Arkham, and you'll have witnessed things you know no one would ever believe. You'll find yourself neck-deep in furtive cultists and their sacrifices, inundated with information about "Ancient Ones" and unholy rituals. And you'll suddenly find yourself forced to destroy terrifying, monstrous creatures that are literally impervious to everything in your arsenal&hellip;

A mystery within a mystery, Undimensioned and Unseen may bring you another step closer to your ultimate goal, but you must first track down whatever knowledge or power may allow you to defeat a number of otherwise invulnerable Abominations. And it demands that you complete your investigation quickly&mdash;possibly by making use of the Mythos Pack&rsquo;s new player cards&mdash;lest you should no longer be the hunter, but the hunted!

There are shadowy plots at work in London, beyond even those of the sinister Cult of Imhotep and its Agents. Ancient forces, who view the smog choked streets and its corrupted masses as anathema to the natural balance of the world, have arisen in the heart of London.

These are the followers of The Wheel. 

Calling forth primal magics, this band of gypsies, witches, and fay now seek to cleanse this black spot from the natural realm- by any means necessary.

The Wheel, an expansion for the game The World of Smog: Rise of Moloch, brings a new missions to Rise of Moloch and comes with:

2 Heroes (Reverend Dudley and Mrs. Dudley);
4 Agents (Nibaba, Baba Yaga the Witch, Divio Juckal and Cobblestone Golem); 
1 New Minion x8 (The Night Creatures); 
Tiles

Defend the Village is a Cooperative Deck-Building game in which 1-5 heroes team up to save a village under distress from low-life bandits and hard-hitting villains! You take turns buying new weapons, potions and helpful items while also fighting off bandits before they destroy all six of your battlegrounds all the while praying you have enough strength to destroy all 5 villains! Do you and your fellow heroes have what it takes to defeat these villains and save this innocent village? Only time will tell&hellip;

Each player is dealt a random Hero with their own stats and ability. Each player also starts with the same starting hand. On each players turn they will reveal a card from the bandit deck and then spend the cards from their hand to purchase new items, or fight a Bandit or Villain.

Easy to learn, tough to survive.

Teams of 2 or more compete to reach the end of the track on the game board. Each turn, one team member rolls a die to determine which of the 4 categories they will attempt.

Oodle Doodles is simple drawing; 
Model Madness involves modelling with clay provided in the box; 
Paper Mash-Ups has the player folding and tearing paper; 
Scribble Riddles requires drawing a phrase, saying or something from popular culture (a song, film or famous person).

The player draws a card from the category that they rolled, and chooses one line from the card. A timer is started, and the other players have to guess what is being drawn or modelled. In some cases, the player is allowed to act and move with the object they are modelling. If the team guess correctly, a miniature representing a marker pen is moved on to the next space of that colour.

Some board spaces have special features. "All Play" means all teams are allowed to guess instead of just the team whose turn it currently is (and move on the board if they guess correctly). "X" means the team moves back by one space if they do not guess correctly. And a "2" means the team has twice the amount of time to guess (the sand timer is turned twice).

To win the game, a team must complete two separate challenges (with two separate rolls of the dice) within the normal time limit, a single turn of the sand timer.

Metras is a game for 3-4 players with an approximate duration of 15 minutes per player. You become the head of a Noble Family of the Empire of Metras seeking the favor of Emperor. You will hold lavish parties, resort to intrigue and corruption, or face epic missions on behalf of the Emperor. 
For your Family to succeed, you will have to place and use allies in key positions to hoard Influence Points (IP), a measure of your power at the Imperial Court.
The winner is the Family who earns the most Influence Points.

The game has 5 turns and the players may perform action by buying action card through an auction from the market using the Influence Point, that you need to win, as coins. 
Action cards are the actions that you can do at the Emperor's court. Each action refers to a one of the four branch of the player's Noble family and they relate to specific aspect of the life at Court.

The branches are:

Fame: this branch indicates the direct influence that the family has on the life at the imperial court;
Exploration: this branch indicates the military and exploratory capacity of the family;
Wealth: this branch indicates, in addition to the assets, the organization and the economic grandeur of the family;
Espionage: this branch indicates the capacity and the amount of spies every family has;

To increase the strength of each branch you must recruit allies or servant that will help you do the actions you bought at auction.

Game contents:
4 boards 25 Instruction Cards 48 Walkers in 4 different colors Instruction page in Hebrew and English

The game's objective:
To be the first player who accumulates 6 Walkers in his chosen color.

What is the game's contribution to us and to our children?
Playing this game strengthens our thinking process and perceptivity skills, it also improves our hand movements, its speed and the attention to small details, and finally it creates a colorful and familial experience with great fun. 
 Strengthens thinking process&hellip;
Improves hand movements and speed&hellip;
Ready, set&hellip;
And here we go&hellip;

&mdash;description from the publisher

Description from the publisher:

A clock shows 4:55am

Yard Boss
&ldquo;I see a couple new faces here today.  Nice.  So Here's the drill.  Contracts come in for freight and passengers every morning starting at 5am.  Trains need to be loaded and out of here by 5:30.  You have exactly 30 mins to complete your tasks.  It is YOUR job to see that ALL contracts are fulfilled.  GOT IT?!?&rdquo;

&ldquo;More than that, make sure you make the railyard money or you are sacked!  Every locomotive, and car you use needs to be fully loaded, or it will cost you your job.  And one more thing, don&rsquo;t overload my trains.  Locomotives can only pull so much.  You blow one of my engines and I will become seriously unpleasant.&rdquo;

&ldquo;Any questions?&rdquo;

"No?"

&ldquo;Excellent"

&ldquo;One more thing to remember, as departure time draws nearer and you see you don&rsquo;t have enough capacity to fill all your contracts, you can always sub them out to one of these mates standing next to you.  You may not get paid for that contract, but it won't count against you when the whistle blows.  You and I get paid when the contracts get filled so make sure there are no contracts in your hand when the whistle blows.&ldquo;

&ldquo;Now get out there and make me some money!&rdquo;

Gameplay is as follow:
Players start with 10 train cards.  Each turn they can either draw 3 cards or play 3 cards.  In order to play cards, you must first play a locomotive and coal car.  Then additional car and cargo can be played.  The correct train car needs to be played in order to place cargo and cargo is the only way to make money.  In the end, if time and running out and there is cargo you cant play, then subcontract it onto another player's train.  You may not get the money for it, but it wont cost you double in the end.  You also might just fill a spot on an opponent's train that they needed.

Each player combines 3 randomly drawn cards to create funny bans, then draw them to make the other players guess what is forbidden.
"No surfing mice with mittens", "No guitar playing for mummies", "No DJ pirates in the shower"&hellip;

The games last 3 rounds, then the player with the most points (from guessing others' bans, and having their own guessed) wins.

MARS WARS is a game of military conflict between Chinese and US space forces comprised of Infantry, drone tanks, and artillery.&nbsp; It is also a game of military conflict between Chinese and US space forces against an alien Martian life.&nbsp;

Using a modified version of Worthington Publishing&rsquo;s HOLD THE LINE system you get scenarios giving you battles that will stand out in Chinese and US history --- Assault on Base Armstrong, The Defense of Ride Ridge, and more.&nbsp; &nbsp;Once the aliens appear you&rsquo;re going to have to fight to hang on against the hordes of aliens, and then root them out of their tunnels.
Each battle&nbsp;lays out your forces, objectives for victory, and the game board.&nbsp; Each turn you receive action points that allow you to order your forces to move and fight.&nbsp; The action points you receive vary from&nbsp;battle&nbsp;to battle&nbsp;and for each side.&nbsp; No two turns or&nbsp;battles will play the same.&nbsp;

Each type of unit moves, attacks and defends differently so using your forces properly is critical to victory.&nbsp;
 The game comes with wooden blocks and labels for three armies (China, US, and Alien), a hard-mounted double sided game board, terrain tiles, rules, battles, and dice.&nbsp; Designed for 2 to&nbsp;6 players (it is playable easily solo by playing both sides as things happen that frustrate the best laid plans).&nbsp; Insignias on the pieces designate at least 3 squads per country&nbsp;that can be played by separate players, plus someone can be the aliens.&nbsp;

Scenarios are playable from 45 &ndash; 90 minutes.&nbsp; Ages 10 and up.

A companion to the main rules of The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey&trade; Strategy Battle Game, focusing on the second and third instalments of The Hobbit: Motion Picture Trilogy, this is a gorgeously-realised, hardback, full-colour book featuring a plethora of new and revised profiles for use in your games of The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey&trade; Strategy Battle Game. Recreate the events of The Hobbit: The Battle of The Five Armies&trade; and The Hobbit: The Desolation of Smaug&trade;!

Featured in the 152-page hardback:


a whopping 25 scenarios continuing those found in The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey&trade; Strategy Battle Game, following the flow of the movies on which they are based &ndash; including the Battle of the Five Armies itself;
    66 new and revised profiles giving you the full range of heroes and monsters to use in your games;
    a detailed campaign system, linking the scenarios together in a way which follows the flow of the movies;
    5 appendix scenarios;
    a collection of army lists, helping you to organise your miniatures into a cohesive force for Points Match games.

Description from the designer:

After a devastating global financial crisis, the nations of the world are down on their knees. To the rescue comes nine political parties hell bent on majority and the transition to progressive democracy&hellip;since dictatorship has that bad ring to it.

In V&auml;rldsregeringen all players take on the role as one of these nine omnipotent parties and commence in a &ldquo;friendly&rdquo; power struggle where everybody must go low, just not as low as their opponents, in the search for new voters that can be swayed. 
The game is played for a predefined number of rounds and in each round the players will be able to execute two different actions before it is time for the parties to argue in debates. The actions available to choose from depend on the number of players and range from gathering campaign resources and get rid of skeletons in the closet to buy voters and politicians. And of course, you can also manipulate the media to get an edge before the debate starts&hellip;

After the actions have been executed each player will have the opportunity to play two arguments in the debate. The player who did the best job of convincing the public of his or her excellence is the winner of the debate which then earns the party a set of voters.

At the end of the game, the party with the most voters are announced the winner and in the aftermath all other parties will be terminated to spare the public from the hard work of voting ever again&hellip;
